  "text": "We find that in the prefrontal cortex the expression of HTR1A significantly decreases during early embryonic development while the expression of HTR5A increases (Fig 5B) . This is also observed in a second human postmortem dataset collected in the prefrontal cortex [CITATION_1] (Fig  5C) . This switch is significant in the primary visual cortex (FDR q-value<10 -4 ), and in the prefrontal cortex (q-value<10 -5 ). These findings complement a recent study by Lambe and colleagues, who analyzed serotonin expression from 59 human subjects aged 6 weeks to 50 years [CITATION_2] . They reported a developmental increase of HTR5A expression in the human prefrontal cortex, paralleled by a stable expression of HTR1A during post-natal development [CITATION_3] . The analysis here shows that these findings continue a trend that started during embryonic development.",
